AIM: 
To write a C program to display student information and marks using structure and union, 
and to demonstrate the difference between the two in terms of memory allocation and data storage. 
 
 
ALGORITHM: 
1. Start the program. 
2. Define a structure StudentStruct with members: 
 -> name (string) 
 -> roll (integer) 
 -> marks (float) 
3. Define a union StudentUnion with the same members: 
 -> name (string) 
 -> roll (integer) 
 -> marks (float) 
4. Declare a structure variable s1 and a union variable u1. 
5. For the structure: 
 -> Read name, roll, and marks from the user. 
 -> Display all three values. 
6. For the union: 
 -> Read name and display it. 
 -> Read roll and display it (note: this overwrites the name). 
 -> Read marks and display it (note: this overwrites the roll). 
7. Explain that in a structure, all members have separate memory locations, 
while in a union, all members share the same memory location. 
8. Stop the program. 
 
 
PROGRAM: 
#include <stdio.h> 
#include <string.h> 
// Structure definition 
struct StudentStruct { 
char name[20]; 
int roll; 
float marks; 
}; 
// Union definition 
union StudentUnion { 
char name[20]; 
int roll; 
float marks; 
}; 
int main() { 
struct StudentStruct s1; 
union StudentUnion u1; 
// Structure data input 
printf("Enter details for Structure:\n"); 
printf("Enter Name: "); 
scanf("%s", s1.name); 
printf("Enter Roll Number: "); 
scanf("%d", &s1.roll); 
printf("Enter Marks: "); 
scanf("%f", &s1.marks); 
// Display structure data 
printf("\nStructure Data:\n"); 
printf("Name: %s\n", s1.name); 
printf("Roll Number: %d\n", s1.roll); 
printf("Marks: %.2f\n", s1.marks); 
// Union data input 
printf("\nEnter details for Union:\n"); 
printf("Enter Name: "); 
scanf("%s", u1.name); 
printf("Name from Union: %s\n", u1.name); 
printf("Enter Roll Number: "); 
scanf("%d", &u1.roll); 
printf("Roll Number from Union: %d\n", u1.roll); 
printf("Enter Marks: "); 
scanf("%f", &u1.marks); 
printf("Marks from Union: %.2f\n", u1.marks); 
// Display memory sizes 
printf("\nSize of Structure: %lu bytes", sizeof(s1)); 
printf("\nSize of Union: %lu bytes\n", sizeof(u1)); 
return 0; 
} 
 
 
 
